{
  "doc_id": "38250",
  "text": "Prior publications using Tg assays with functional sensitivities of 1.0 -3.0 ng/ml have suggested that tumor recurrence after a patient is declared free of disease occurs in less than 0.5-1.5% [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] ). Previously we reported an incidence of 1.6% among patients with an rhTSH-Tg of 0.5 ng/ml or less when this cohort was followed up for 3-5 yr (6). Now after being followed up a mean of 7 yr (range 0.8 -10.9 yr), 3% of patients who initially demonstrated an rhTSH-Tg of 0.5 ng/ml or less have had recurrent disease. The prevalence of recurrence is 11% when the first rhTSH-Tg was 0.6 -2.0 ng/ml. In patients whose first rhTSH-Tg was greater than 2.0 ng/ml, the prevalence of eventual recurrent tumor was 80%. Because 10% of these last patients (group 3) were lost to follow-up within 1 yr, this prevalence of recurrent disease could be even higher. Although the risk of tumor recurrence across rhTSH-Tg values between 0.5 and 5 ng/ml is likely a continuum, we saw distinct differences between our patient groups in which tumor recurrence occurred significantly sooner and more often in group 3 than in groups 1 and 2 (both P Ͻ 0.001), whereas groups 1 and 2 were not significantly different (P ϭ 0.25). The mean time (ϮSD) to recurrence in groups 1-3 was 4.1 Ϯ 1.6, 3.1 Ϯ 1.3, and 2.0 Ϯ 1.4 yr, respectively (Fig. 2) .",
